Multiplying the second equation by $2$ will remove the coefficient of $y$ from both equations.
\begin{aligned}2x - y &= 5 \\ 2(x + 2y) &= \; &10\text{ ( }\leftarrow2(5)\text{)} \end{aligned}
Working on the second equation, let's distribute the $2$ throughout the parentheses.
\begin{aligned}2x - y &= 5 \\ 2x + 4y &= \; &10\text{ (}\;\text{)}
\end{aligned}
Now let's add the two equations together because opposites add to $0$.
\begin{aligned}\text{ }2x - y &= 5 \\ 2x + 4y &= 10\text{ }\text{ }\Rightarrow\text{ }6y\text{ }=\text{ }15\text{ }\text{ }\end{aligned}
Let's solve for $y$ by dividing both sides by $6$.
\begin{aligned}6y &= 15 \ \Rightarrow \ 6y\text{/}\!\!\div6 = 15\text{/}\!\!\div6 \\ y&= \frac{15}{6}\end{aligned}
Let's substitute the value of $y$ into the first equation in order to solve for $x$.
